atinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joyce de Walbieffe was born about 1286, in Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom, her father, John de Walbieffe, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. John de Walbieffe, was 25. She had at least 3 sons with Roger Ieuanc ap Roger Fawr."},"et":{"Abt 1286–":"umbes 1286–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1349–1415":"1349–1415","1259–Male":"1259–Surnud","1263–Female":"1263–Surnud","1415":"1415","1349":"1349","1259":"1259","about 1349":"umbes 1349","Abt 1286":"umbes 1286","1320":"1320","1286":"1286","1263":"1263","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England":"Bredwardine, Herefordshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Canteff-Selyff, Brecknock, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"Abt 1286–":"noin 1286–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1349–1415":"1349–1415","1259–Male":"1259–Kuollut","1263–Female":"1263–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1349":"1349","1259":"1259"